Project#5 of AI Course of University of Tehran¶

Rasta Tadayon - 810196436

Image Classification Using Neural Networks and Pytorch

Brief Description of The Project

In this project the objective is categorizing images into 52 categories of goods such as shoes, Tshirts, accessories, etc. To do so Neural Networks are used and during the project effects of diferent parameters are evaluated on the network. For implementation of the network Pytorch library of Python is used. The input images are given via google drive and are unzipped and used in the learning process.

Neural Networks¶

Neural networks are a set of algorithms, modeled loosely after the human brain, that are designed to recognize patterns. Just like the neural network in human brain, Artificial Neural Network consists of neurons (nodes) and connections between those neurons. Nodes in a neral network are grouped into layers. The layers between the input layer and output layer are called hidden layers. The connections of the biological neuron are modeled as weights in the artifial network. In the layers, output of a neuron is the input to the later neuron. To calculate the output of a neural network the propagation function computes the input to a neuron from the outputs of its predecessor neurons and their connections as a weighted sum. Each node can also have a bias term which is added to the weighted sum in order to make the model fit better to a given data.

In [3]:
class CustomToTensor(object):
    """Convert PIL Images in sample to pytorch Tensors."""
    
    ## the input image must be grayscaled first
    def __call__(self, image):
        image = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)
        # numpy image: H x W
        return torch.from_numpy(image)

After the images are loaded transforms are applied to them. In this project for simplicity gray scale tranform is applied to eliminate the effect of colors in the learning process. Also in this part a custom transform is applied to the images which makes the image array into 32bit floating point numpy array and then creates a tensor object from that array and returns the tensor object.

def get_number_distribution(loader, classes):
  total_category_count = {classes[i] : 0 for i in range(len(classes))}
  for _, labels in loader:
    for label in labels:
      total_category_count[ classes[label] ] += 1
  return total_category_count

number_of_each_class = get_number_distribution(dataloaders, classes)
sorted_list = sorted(number_of_each_class.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=False)
sorted_dict = {sorted_list[i][0] : sorted_list[i][1] for i in range (len(sorted_list))}

2-b : Splitting Data into Train and Test Set¶

In this part the dataset is split into test and train set. To do so for each class 80% of its data will be placed by random in the train set and 20% will be placed in the test set. An alternative for this splitting action is to take 80% of the whole dataset and put it in the train set and 20% in the test set however this may cause for a class not to be presented well in the train set therfore the model will not be able to have a good accuracy on that specific class.

For the splitting the sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split() function is used which does the task that we want done.

In [11]:

PART 3 : Creating the Neual Network Model¶

The neural network is created by setting the number of neruons in each layer and setting the activation function for each layer as well. For the number of input and output nodes in each layer I have scaled the number of the nodes in the recitation file since the image size of this project was three times of the recitations. For the number of total layer 5 was decided to be just like the recitation and it was observed later that this number works pretty well.

The forward() function reshapes its input, x, to a tensor with x.size columns and appropriate rows per columns then if forwards x through the network.

In [13]:
class Model(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, class_num, act=F.relu):
        super(Model, self).__init__()


        self.layer1 = nn.Linear(1 * 60 * 80, 12 * 60 * 20) # layer 1 input: 4800   output: 14400
        self.act1 = act


        self.layer2 = nn.Linear(12 * 60 * 20, 30 * 14 * 10) # layer 2 input: 14400  output: 4200
        self.act2 = act



        self.layer3 = nn.Linear(30 * 14 * 10, 70 * 30 * 1) # layer 3 input: 4200    output: 2100
        self.act3 = act


        self.layer4 = nn.Linear(70 * 30 * 1, 250 * 2 *1)  # layer 4 input: 2100     output: 500
        self.act4 = act

        self.layer5 = nn.Linear(250 * 2 *1, class_num)    # layer 5 input: 500      output: 52

    def forward(self, x):

        x = x.view(x.size(0), -1)

        x = self.layer1(x)
        x = self.act1(x)

        x = self.layer2(x)
        x = self.act2(x)

        x = self.layer3(x)
        x = self.act3(x)

        x = self.layer4(x)
        x = self.act4(x)

        x = self.layer5(x)
        return x

3-a : Counting the Number of Trainable Parameters in the Network¶

The function count_parameters() counts the parameters of the model that can be trained. In this model those are the weights and biases. For counting of the parameters the named_parameters() function is used.

In [15]:

Hyperpatameters used for the training are like follows:

  • Learning rate = 0.01
  • Number of epoches = 10
  • Loss Criterion = Cross Entropy
  • Activation Funcrtion = Relu
  • Optimizer = Stochastic Gradient Descent

Cross Entropy

This criterion is useful when training a classification problem with C classes. Pytorch documentation of it can be found here.

ReLU

ReLU is short for Rectified Linear Unit and works like this:

if (x > 0) return x else return 0

In [16]:
def count_parameters(model):
    total_param = 0
    for name, param in model.named_parameters():
        if param.requires_grad:
            num_param = np.prod(param.size())
            if param.dim() > 1:
                print(name, ':', 'x'.join(str(x) for x in list(param.size())), '=', num_param)
            else:
                print(name, ':', num_param)
            total_param += num_param
    return total_param

count_parameters(model)

layer1.weight : 14400x4800 = 69120000
layer1.bias : 14400
layer2.weight : 4200x14400 = 60480000
layer2.bias : 4200
layer3.weight : 2100x4200 = 8820000
layer3.bias : 2100
layer4.weight : 500x2100 = 1050000
layer4.bias : 500
layer5.weight : 52x500 = 26000
layer5.bias : 52
Out[16]:
139517252

As mentioned before the connection of neurons are modeled as weights in the Artificial Network and the network is fully connected. Also each node has a bias value. Therefore each layer has [number of input nodes][number of out put nodes] weights and [number of layer nodes] bias values. Summation of all the weight and bias values of each layer will produce the total number of trainable parameters in the network.

In [17]:
def fit(model, train_loader, device, criterion, optimizer, num_epochs=epoch_num):

  total_time = 0.
  average_losses = []
  for epoch in range(num_epochs):
      train_loss = 0.
      d1 = datetime.now()
      for images, labels in train_loader:
          
        images = images.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)

        # Clear gradients w.r.t. parameters
        optimizer.zero_grad()

        # Forward pass to get output/logits
        outputs = model(images)

        # Calculate Loss: softmax --> cross entropy loss
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

        # Getting gradients w.r.t. parameters
        loss.backward()

        # Updating parameters
        optimizer.step()
        train_loss += loss.item()

      average_loss = train_loss / len(train_loader)
      average_losses.append(average_loss)
      d2 = datetime.now()
      delta = d2 - d1
      seconds = float(delta.total_seconds())
      total_time += seconds
      print('epoch %d, train_loss: %.3f, time elapsed: %s seconds' % (epoch + 1, average_loss, seconds))
  print('total training time: %.3f minutes' % (total_time / 60))
  return average_losses

In [19]:
def test_model_accuracy(model, test_loader):
    # Calculate Accuracy         
    correct = 0.
    total = 0.
    # Iterate through test dataset
    with torch.no_grad():
      for images, labels in test_loader:
        outputs = model(images.to(device))
        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
        total += labels.size(0)
        correct += (predicted.to('cpu') == labels).sum().item()

    accuracy = 100 * correct / total
    return accuracy

In [22]:
def confusion_matrix(model, data_loader, class_num):
  confusion_matrix = np.zeros(shape=(class_num,class_num)) 
  #vertical is for the actual label and horizontal is for the prediction
  with torch.no_grad():
    for images, labels in data_loader:
      outputs = model(images.to(device))
      _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
      for i in range(labels.size(0)):
        confusion_matrix[labels[i]][predicted[i]] += 1
  return confusion_matrix
In [23]:
train_cm = confusion_matrix(model, train_loader, len(classes))
test_cm = confusion_matrix(model, test_loader, len(classes))

It is observable above that the train loss values are "nan" which means they are so large that they can not fit into a number or something like log(0) and therefore are not a number. The reason why the loss values are nan is because the tensor values are not normalized and are between [0, 255]. When training loss becomes NaN it could be a sign of Gradient explosion.

Gradient explosion happens in deep networks or recurrent neural networks when gradients can accumulate (sometimes exponentially) during an update and result in very large gradients. These in turn result in large updates to the network weights, which result in an unstable network. At an extreme, the values of weights can become so large as to overflow and result in NaN values. The weights are printed above and can be seen that have become nan values.

This is the most probable cause in this part. Because of this problem the model is not learning at all therefore predicting class 0 for all of the inputs. (the reason for that is the max function returns the first value if the arguments are of the same value resulting in the class 0 prediction.)

In [24]:
def accuracy_for_each_class(confusion_matrix):
  total = sum(sum(confusion_matrix))
  accuracy = [0] * len(confusion_matrix)
  temp = 0
  for i in range(len(confusion_matrix)):
    # accuracy[i] = (total - (sum(confusion_matrix[:][i]) + 
    #                        sum(confusion_matrix[i][:]) - 2 * confusion_matrix[i][i])) / total * 100
    accuracy[i] = confusion_matrix[i][i]/sum(confusion_matrix[i][:]) * 100
  return accuracy
In [25]:
def plot_bar_chart(train_accuracy, test_accuracy):
  barWidth = 0.35
  r1 = np.arange(len(classes))
  r2 = [x + barWidth for x in r1]
  f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,10))
  plt.bar(r1, train_accuracy, color='#7f6d5f', width=barWidth, edgecolor='white', label='train set')
  plt.bar(r2, test_accuracy, color='#557f2d', width=barWidth, edgecolor='white', label='test set')
  
  # Add xticks on the middle of the group bars
  plt.xlabel('classes', fontweight='bold')
  plt.xticks([r + barWidth for r in range(len(train_accuracy))], classes, rotation = 90)
  plt.ylabel('accuracy values', fontweight='bold')
  
  # Create legend & Show graphic
  plt.legend()
  plt.show()

PART 4 : Normalizing the Images¶

In this part a new transform is defined which brings the values of image tensor from 0-255 to 0-1 thus normalizing and restricting the values the input vector can have. Normalization changes the numeric values of the tensor image to a common scale without distoting differenecs in the ranges of values.

Normalizing the data often results in faster convergance. Also in this part it is observable that since the values have been restricted to be between 0 and 1 the gradient explosion does not happen and the model is able to train.

In [29]:
class custom_to_tensor(object):
    """Convert PIL Images in sample to pytorch Tensors."""
    
    ## the input image must be grayscaled first
    def __call__(self, image):
        image = np.array(image, dtype=np.float32)/255
        # numpy image: H x W
        return torch.from_numpy(image)

PART 5 : Initializing Weights to Zero¶

In this part all the weights including biases are initialized to zero using the model.apply() function. This function applies a given function recursively to every submodule (as returned by .children() ) as well as self (model itself).

In [36]:
def zeros_(m):
    if(type(m) == nn.Linear):
      nn.init.zeros_(m.weight)
      m.bias.data.fill_(0)

model_5 = Model(len(classes))
model_5 = model_5.to(device)

model_5.apply(zeros_)

optimizer_5 = torch.optim.SGD(model_5.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)

average_losses_5 = fit(model_5, train_loader_4, device, criterion, optimizer_5, epoch_num)

max(model_5.layer5.bias)
Out[54]:
tensor(1.7074, device='cuda:0', grad_fn=<SelectBackward>)

It is observable that initializing weights to zero is not a good idea and does not result in good accuracy. The reasoning is as follows:

When all the weights are initialized with 0, the derivative with respect to loss function is the same for every value in weight vector, thus all weights have the same value in subsequent iterations. This makes hidden units symmetric and continues for all the n iterations i.e. setting weights to 0 does not make it better than a linear model. Also biases do not have any effect since they are zero as well. This means initializing all the weights with zeros leads the neurons to learn the same features during training.

Here all of the weights of the network are not changed during the training and are zero after the training is done except for the bias values of the output layer. The reason for that is during back propagation the gradients are multiplied by the weights of network therefore are always zero. Except the bias value of the last layer which is updated by the gradient of error function. Resulting the class with the highest number of data to have larger bias and for the network to predict every input into that class

5-b : The Best Way to Initialize Weights¶

As mentioned before initializing weights to zero will result in a model that does not fit our data very well. Any constant value that the weights are all set to will make all the nodes learn the same features therefore is not a good option. Other options are to randomly initialize the weights.

When initializing weights randomly one thing to be aware of is that if weights are initialized to high values or very low values what happens and also what is a reasonable initialization of weight values.

  • A too-large initialization leads to exploding gradients : This means when the weight values are too large the values of activation increase exponentially. When these activations are used in backward propagation, this leads to the gradients of the cost with the respect to the parameters being too big. This leads the cost to oscillate around its minimum value.
  • A too-small initialization leads to vanishing gradients : This means when the weight values are too small values of the activation decrease exponentially. When these activations are used in backward propagation, this leads to the vanishing gradient problem. The gradients of the cost with respect to the parameters are too small, leading to convergence of the cost before it has reached the minimum value.

Better Weight Initialization Methods:

  • Using ReLu / leaky ReLU as the activation function: These activation functions are relatively robust to the vanishing/exploding gradient issues

  • Using heuristic to initialize the wights depending on the non linear activation function: for ReLu the randomly generated weight values are multiplied by np.sqrt(2/size_l-1). For Tanh the heuristic is called Xavier Initialization. in this one the randomly generated values are multiplied by np.sqrt(1/size_l-1)

  • Gradient Clipping: This is another way of dealing with the exploding gradient problem. The objective is setting a threshold value and if a chosen function of gradient is larger than this threshold, it will be set to another value.

Also using an already learnt network's weights is a possible way of initializing the weight values specially for general and large networks.

PART 6 : Chacking Different Learning Rates¶

In [ ]:
def check_learning_rates(learning_rate):
  print('Learning Rate = ', learning_rate)
  model_6 = Model(len(classes))
  model_6 = model_6.to(device)
  optimizer_6 = torch.optim.SGD(model_6.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
  average_losses_6 = fit(model_6, train_loader_4, device, criterion, optimizer_6, epoch_num)

  test_acc = test_model_accuracy(model_6, test_loader_4)
  train_acc = test_model_accuracy(model_6, train_loader_4)
  
  print('\nAccuracy:\nTest: ', test_acc, '\nTrain: ', train_acc)
  train_cm_6 = confusion_matrix(model_6, train_loader_4, len(classes))
  test_cm_6 = confusion_matrix(model_6, test_loader_4, len(classes))
  train_accuracy_6 = accuracy_for_each_class(train_cm_6)
  test_accuracy_6 = accuracy_for_each_class(test_cm_6)


  plot_bar_chart(train_accuracy_6, test_accuracy_6)
  plot_avarage_loss(average_losses_6)

  return train_acc, test_acc, average_losses_6

In [ ]:
def plot_test_accuracy_curve(learning_rate, accuracy):
  f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
  plt.plot(learning_rate, accuracy)
  plt.xlabel('Learning Rate', fontweight='bold')
  plt.ylabel('Accuracy', fontweight='bold')
  plt.xticks(learning_rate, rotation = 90)
  plt.title('Accuracy for Different Learning Rates')

accuracies = [test_acc_002, test_acc_004, test_acc_006, test_acc_008,
              test_acc_01, test_acc_03, test_acc_05, test_acc_07, test_acc_09]
plot_test_accuracy_curve(learning_rates, accuracies)

In this part different values of learning rates were used and accuracy for each of the values were obtained. The tested values are: 0.002, 0.004, 0.006, 0.008. 0.01, 0.03, 0.05, 0.07, 0.09. The best learning rate was 0.05. (Accuracy for 0.07 was higher but the practice is that the best learning rate is one on the way to the peak and not the peak itself)

PART 7: Checking the Impact of Different Batch Sizes¶

In [ ]:
def check_different_batch_size(batch_size_, learning_rate_ = opt_lr):
  print('Batch Size = ', batch_size_)
  train_loader_7 = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(X_train_4, batch_size=batch_size_,
                                          shuffle=True, num_workers=32)

  test_loader_7 = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(X_test_4, batch_size=batch_size_,
                                         shuffle=False, num_workers=32)
  model_7 = Model(len(classes))
  model_7 = model_7.to(device)
  optimizer_7 = torch.optim.SGD(model_7.parameters(), lr=learning_rate_)
  average_losses_7 = fit(model_7, train_loader_7, device, criterion, optimizer_7, epoch_num)

  test_acc = test_model_accuracy(model_7, test_loader_7)
  train_acc = test_model_accuracy(model_7, train_loader_7)
  
  print('\nAccuracy:\nTest: ', test_acc, '\nTrain: ', train_acc)
  train_cm_7 = confusion_matrix(model_7, train_loader_7, len(classes))
  test_cm_7 = confusion_matrix(model_7, test_loader_7, len(classes))
  train_accuracy_7 = accuracy_for_each_class(train_cm_7)
  test_accuracy_7 = accuracy_for_each_class(test_cm_7)


  plot_bar_chart(train_accuracy_7, test_accuracy_7)
  plot_avarage_loss(average_losses_7)

  # return train_acc, test_acc, average_losses_7

total training time: 8.018 minutes

Accuracy:
Test:  71.28859060402685 
Train:  72.74405181381925

In smaller batch sizes these are some of the things that can happen:

  • lower minimum validation loss. (this is not shown in this project because the validation loss was not calculated)
  • more time it takes to train per epoch. (because of the overhead of the changing between batches along with the fact that if the batch size is too small parallisation is not possible since it starts to look like sequential iterations.)
  • less epochs to converge to the minimum validation loss. this can cause less total time to converge to a minimum cost.
  • smaller batch sizes will generalize better because smaller batch sizes converge to flatter minimizers.
  • the final weights are farther away from the initial weights in smaller batch sizes than in larger ones. This can mean elimination of effect of poor initial weights.
  • each batch is a “noisy” representation of the entire dataset and seeing many batches, will cause a sort of “tug-and-pull” dynamic. This dynamic prevents the neural network from overfitting on the training set.

In this part we can see that time of each epoch has increased significantly and the the accuracy has also increased significantly which matches out initial belief.

total training time: 3.739 minutes

Accuracy:

In larger batch sizes these are some of the things that can happen:

  • higher minimum validation loss. (this is not shown in this project because the validation loss was not calculated)
  • less time it takes to train per epoch. (because of the lower overhead associated with loading a smaller number of large batches, as opposed to many small batches sequentially.)
  • more epochs to converge to the minimum validation loss. this can cause more total time to converge to a minimum cost.
  • too large of a batch size will result in poor generalization because large batch sizes converge to sharp minimizers.
  • the final weights are closer to the initial weights in larger batch sizes than in smaller ones.
  • is more likely to converge to the global minima.
  • is more prone to overfitting to the train data.

In this part we can see that time of each epoch has dropped significantly but the accuracy is not as good as batch size = 64. This maybe because with larger batch sizes it takes more epoches to converge.

With larger batch sizes larger learning rates work better than smaller learning rates as is observable in the above that with a high learning rate (0.12) the accuracy is significantly better than with a smaller learning rate (0.008). The reason behind that is since the batch size is larger when changing the weights the change is representing a larger number of data which is less likely to be noise therefore if the learning rate is greater when the batch size is big the model is more likely to have good accuracy.

PART 8: Observing the Effects of Momentum on the Model¶

8-a : What is momentum and what are its pros and cons:¶

Momentum can be in a way thought of as a non-static learning rate.

Momentum is a method that helps accelerate SGD in the relevant direction and dampens oscillations around the local optimum. It does this by adding a fraction γ of the update vector of the past time step to the current update vector :

vt = γvt−1+η∇θJ(θ)

θ = θ−vt

The momentum term increases for dimensions whose gradients point in the same directions and reduces updates for dimensions whose gradients change directions. As a result, we gain faster convergence and reduced oscillation. In Stochastic Gradient Descent since the exact derivate of loss function is not being calculated because the loss function on a batch is calculated therefore the weights might not always be on the path to the optimal direction, because our derivatives are ‘noisy’. So, using momentum can provide a better estimate which is closer to the actual derivate than the noisy calculations.

When using momentum too small values can make the weights fluctuate and when using too large of a value the weights may have a smooth transition but the weights might shift away from the correct values.

8-b:¶

In this part momentum values of 0.5, 0.9, 0.98 were tested for our model.

def check_different_momentums(momentum_, learning_rate_=opt_lr):

It is observable that for the 0.5 momentum value the model is working much better than without momentum, however for 0.9 momentum value the model is not doing a good job which might be because the model is missing the local optima. This is seen in the graph that after epoch 4 the loss is oscillating.

The intresting thing is when momentum value is equal to 0.98. In this case the model works like the one from section 3, meaning it is not learning at all and having nan train loss values. The reason for this can be because the learning rate is a relatively large value, so the model will not be able to decrease the gradient values and the steps get too large and the weights start to get too big and gradient explosion happens. Since the momentum is some what creating a variable learning rate and the steps are already quite big, the momentum amplifies the effect and results in gradient explosion.

Adding momentum values has added around 7 seconds to the time per epoch.

8-c: Does increase in momentum necessarily result in higher accuracy?¶

The answer to that is no.

As seen in the previous part, best momentum value were 0.5 and 0.9 and 0.98 did not work properly.

Too big of a momentum could make the model overshoot the local optima and start oscillating around in and not converge.

9-a¶

When the epoch numbers are increased to 20 the model works better with much accuracy and lower training loss. This is because the training is continuing on for more time therefore the weights are getting closer to the right values however it has made the training time increase around two times.

9-b : Why more than one epoch is needed?¶

Stochastic Gradient Descent is an iterative learning algorithm that uses a training dataset to update a model. The number of epochs is a hyperparameter of gradient descent that controls the number of times the whole data is being forwarded through the network. Since SGD is an iterative learning algorithm more than one epochs are needed to train the model correctly.

9-b : Is increase in the number of epochs always good?¶

Increase in the number of epoches does not always result in better accuracy on the test set because then the model may start to overfit to the training set. However the epoch value should be as large as possible as long as the train loss is still decreasing and training should stop when the training loss curve almost flats out.

PART 10 : Observing the Effect of Activation Functions on the Model¶

Read this link for more information on this subject.

Until this part the activation function used for the model was ReLU. In this part Leaky_ReLU and Tanh are used and effects of them on the training is observed:

ReLU:¶

ReLU as mentioned before works like this: x if x > 0 else 0

Advantages of ReLU:

  • ReLU has a very cheap to computation cost.
  • It should converge faster than sigmoid or tanh function (but here we observe that tanh actually has decreased the training loss with a faster rate)
  • Does not have the vanishing gradients problem.

Disadvantages of ReLU:

  • Since all negative values will turn into zero if once a neuron gets negative it is unlikely that it will recover. This is called “dying ReLU” problem.
  • ReLU can get prone to exploding gradients with large input value of large learning rates which we observed happened in different ocasions.

Leaky_ReLU:¶

Leacky_ReLU is a varient of ReLU and what it does is that in an attempt ot solve the dying ReLU problem it generates very small negative values instead of zero when the x is negative.

When using Leaky_ReLU instead of ReLU itself the model works just a little better but they have quite similar results.

Tanh:¶

The tanh function applies the following on the output of the node:

(2/1+exp(-2x)) - 1. This activation function is a non linear one.

  • It is nonlinear in nature, so stacking of the layers is possible.
  • It is bound in the range of [-1, 1]
  • It can have the vanishing gradient problem.
  • It works better than sigmoid function because the negative inputs will be mapped strongly negative and the zero inputs will be mapped near zero in the tanh graph.

Some points to keep in mind are:

  • The sigmoid and tanh activation functions cannot be used in networks with many layers due to the vanishing gradient problem.
  • When learning rate is large ReLU should be used with caution.

In this part, the tanh activation function worked better than ReLU and Leaky_ReLU.

PART 11 : Observing the Effects of Regularization¶

11-a: How does adding regulizer term in the loss function help with overfitting?¶

Minimizing the training error is a reasonable thing to do, but it’s possible that the model becomes overfit to the train data.

Regularization means modifying a learning algorithm to result in simpler prediction rules thus avoiding overfitting. Most commonly, regularization refers to modifying the loss function to penalize certain values of the weights you are learning specifically, penalize weights that are large.

How the penilization works is something like this:

L(w) + λ R(w)¶

L(w) is the loss function that's being used.

R(w) is called the regularization term or regularizer or penalty.

λ is the hyperparameter that adjusts the tradeoff between having low training loss and having low weights.

Regularization helps the computational problem because it can prevent gradient explosion since the effects of large weight vector becomes more noticable than the gain in loss function.

There are differnet regularization terms such as L1, L2, etc.

When R(w) = ||w||^2 It is called L2 regularization.

When R(w) = ||w|| It is called L1 regularizarion.

The L2 regularization is used by default in the SGD optimizer.

11-b: weight_decay term in optimizer function?¶

As stated before the regularization term by default in SGD optimizer is L2 and the weight_decay parameter is the λ value. Adding this parameter to the optimizer function means adding the penilizing term therefore adding the regularization.

11-c : Setting weight_decay equal to 0.1¶

In this part model was trained with weight)decay equal to 0.1.

In [ ]:
def set_regulizer(weight_decay_):
  print("Weight Decay Value: ", weight_decay_)
  model_11 = Model(len(classes))
  model_11 = model_11.to(device)
  optimizer_11 = torch.optim.SGD(model_11.parameters(), lr=opt_lr, momentum=opt_momentum, weight_decay=weight_decay_)
  average_losses_11 = fit(model_11, train_loader_4, device, criterion, optimizer_11, epoch_num)

  test_acc = test_model_accuracy(model_11, test_loader_4)
  train_acc = test_model_accuracy(model_11, train_loader_4)
  
  print('\nAccuracy:\nTest: ', test_acc, '\nTrain: ', train_acc)
  train_cm_11 = confusion_matrix(model_11, train_loader_4, len(classes))
  test_cm_11 = confusion_matrix(model_11, test_loader_4, len(classes))
  train_accuracy_11 = accuracy_for_each_class(train_cm_11)
  test_accuracy_11 = accuracy_for_each_class(test_cm_11)


  plot_bar_chart(train_accuracy_11, test_accuracy_11)
  plot_avarage_loss(average_losses_11)
